<!--
VOICING PLAN — It Came Upon A Midnight Clear (Bb major, 6/8):

6/8 compound meter shapes the arrangement: each bar has 2 compound beats (dotted-quarter),
so the harp voicings change on beat 1 and beat 2 within each bar. This gives the natural
lilting feel of 6/8 without overcrowding.

Phrase 1 (mm. pickup–4): Opens with a single pickup F4 in both melody and RH. M1 uses
the characteristic I→ii7→IV motion that defines this carol. LH carries "334" (4-note)
voicings on beat 1, relaxing to 3-note on beat 2. M2 and M4 establish the V (F) pedal
under sustained melody notes.

Borrowed passage (M9): D7 is a secondary dominant (V7/vi), tonicizing Gm in M10.
Since D7 contains F# (non-diatonic in Bb), the harp plays diatonic Gm and Dm
harmonies underneath — the melody's E-natural and F# pass as solo color tones.
This maintains harp diatonicism while honoring the chromatic melody.

Phrase 3 (mm. 9–12): The Gm tonicization adds modal color. M10 oscillates Gm→Dm
with open-fifth LH voicings. M11 descends through V (F major) with a 6-note
descending melody run — harp holds long F-major "334" voicings to give breathing room.

Final verse (mm. 13–16): Reprises mm. 1–7 exactly (same voicings for stability),
then closes on I in M16 with full "334" LH and "33" RH — settled and warm.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- M1→M2: RH D5→A4 (falling 5th into I), LH D4→Bb3 (falling 3rd). Contrary motion.
- M3: Both hands ascend stepwise (IV→vii°→Cm) mirroring the rising melody.
- M7→M8: V7 (Eb in bass) resolves to I (Bb), all voices step downward. Classic resolution.
- M15→M16: Same V7→I resolution as M7→M8, confirming the final cadence.

TEXTURE ARC:
- Pickup–M2: Lightest (2 RH notes, 3–4 LH). Single-note RH pickup.
- M3–M6: Middle texture, 2+3 to 2+4 notes.
- M8–M10: Climax region — full 4-note LH on each beat, RH 2-note at top register.
- M12–M16: Settling back, with final bar holding simple I voicings to close.
-->
